The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Monday, August 23, 2004  Business Briefs																								 Mumbai, Aug. 22: The retail investors who had participated in the initial public offering for Tata Consultancy Services Ltd will get 17 shares of Re 1 each against 50 applied for, according to merchant banking sources. The Tata group company, which will list its stock on the NSE and the BSE on August 25, has also decided to exercise the green-shoe option comprising over 80 lakh shares. The retail portion of the public offer was oversubscribed by 2.9 times and offer had received total 13.5 lakh application, sources said here today.																								 New Delhi, Aug. 22: Air Deccan, the countrys first low-cost airline, is all set to launch its long-haul operations between Delhi and Mumbai from Wednesday. Though the civil aviation ministry made last-minute inquiries into the maintenance aspects of the private carrier.																								 New Delhi, Aug. 22: Bankers have cautioned that tightening of monetary policy by the Reserve Bank to arrest inflationary pressures may jeopardise the governments mandate to step up farm credit by 30 per cent to Rs 1,04,500 crore this fiscal.																								 New Delhi, Aug. 22: The government is considering allowing navratna PSUs to invest up to 10 per cent of their net worth for acquisitions and joint ventures on their own.																								 New Delhi, Aug. 22: Japanese automaker Nissan Motor Co plans to launch light commercial vehicles and cars in India and make the country a sourcing base for components, said senior vice-president Toshiyukkki Shiga.
